ss target even with a test provider. I’m unsure if I should use the actual provider class, like org.jcp.xml.dsig.internal.dom.XMLDSigRI, or check dependencies like xmlsec. For JDK 17+, maybe the org.jcp provider in java.xml.crypto is accessible. I need to consider if reflection on JDK internal classes might fail without the right metadata. Testing is definitely needed!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Evaluating test strategies**\\\\n\\\\nI'm considering whether to compile or run tests, but we’ve been instructed not to do that. Using jshell might be a workaround while avoiding tests, and I wonder if inspecting the JDK directly is a better idea. I think I can utilize knowledge about dependencies without running anything. For instance, POI 4.1.2 depends on xmlsec, which includes org.apache.jcp.xml.dsig.internal.dom.XMLDSigRI. I’ll need to create an active class test, possibly by replacing the placeholder with a dedicated SignatureConfigTest.java.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Reassessing test structure**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking about whether tests should focus solely on the active class. The placeholder doesn't seem to involve dynamic access, and the \\\\\\\"one-to-one mapping\\\\\\\" suggests that there shouldn't be a scaffold placeholder. It might make sense to replace the placeholder's content with a public non-test smoke. However, I still believe that each dynamic-access class should have its own dedicated file. I need to clarify my approach to ensure everything is aligned correctly.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_o2PX5Sgpv8xyLYA1P9JuSgRQ|fc_0d5c35933d983d54016a2713b75f888197aa6b9b4c8ce1c1bd\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"grep -n \\\"setProvider\\\\|getProvider\\\" -n /home/mihailo/git/graalvm-reachability-metadata-copy/.agents/worktrees/oracle-graalvm-reachability-metadata-issue-7628-library-specific-preparation-preflight/forge/local_repositories/source_context/org.apache.poi/poi-ooxml/4.1.2/main/extracted/org/apache/poi/poifs/crypt/dsig/SignatureConfig.java\"}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"oca/gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 536, \"output\": 1231, \"cacheRead\": 21504, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 23271, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1780945819027, \"responseId\": \"resp_0d5c35933d983d54016a27139bd4fc81979b6180e78ae2c19a\"}}\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.apache.poi:poi-ooxml:4.1.2/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-06-08T19-12-55-749866Z.log:1107:[tool-exec] start id=call_o2PX5Sgpv8xyLYA1P9JuSgRQ|fc_0d5c35933d983d54016a2713b75f888197aa6b9b4c8ce1c1bd name=bash args={\"command\": \"grep -n \\\"setProvider\\\\|getProvider\\\" -n /home/mihailo/git/graalvm-reachability-metadata-copy/.agents/worktrees/oracle-graalvm-reachability-metadata-issue-7628-library-specific-preparation-preflight/forge/local_repositories/source_context/org.apache.poi/poi-ooxml/4.1.2/main/extracted/org/apache/poi/poifs/crypt/dsig/SignatureConfig.java\"}\nhuman-intervention-logs/org.apache.poi:poi-ooxml:4.1.2/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-06-08T19-12-55-749866Z.log:1119:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Exploring class access and dependencies**\\n\\nI'm thinking about the conditional agent and whether it only includes org.apache.poi callers. It might record the class target even with a test provider. I’m unsure if I should use the actual provider class, like org.jcp.xml.dsig.internal.dom.XMLDSigRI, or check dependencies like xmlsec. For JDK 17+, maybe the org.jcp provider in java.xml.crypto is accessible. I need to consider if reflection on JDK internal classes might fail without the right metadata. Testing is definitely needed!\\n\\n**Evaluating test strategies**\\n\\nI'm considering whether to co